oping countries, particularly those in Latin America and East Asia, although many lessons of the study should apply as well to other, poorer debtor countries. The project analyzes the crisis from two perspectives, that of the international financial system as a whole (volume 1) and that of individual debtor countries (volumes 2 and 3). This second volume contains lengthy and detailed case studies of four Latin American nations—Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, and Mexico—providing a wealth of comparative data and new statistics on the general economic development of each nation. The authors explore the various factors that contributed to the debt crisis in each country and analyze how the crisis was managed once it had taken hold. Trenchant economic analyses are enchanced by assessments of the stark political realities behind the policy choices facing each nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  amexico, argentina, bolivia, brazil, economics, debt, growth, economy, economic development, poverty, international capital market, default, macroeconomy, global financial markets, developing countries, finance, inflation, budget, price dynamics, capitalism, state, trade policy, macroeconomics, hyperinflation, stabilization, intermediation, underemployment, real wages, import compression, nonfiction.1 aAntonio Morales, Juan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuffie, Edward F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCardoso, Eliana A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlos de Pablo, Juan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDornbusch, Rudiger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFishlow, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo